{{about|the English ship|the Indian city|Allahabad|other uses|Allahabad (disambiguation)}}

'''''Allahabad''''' was an iron [[sailing ship]] of 1,190 tons gross and 1,143 tons net register. It was built in [[Liverpool]] in 1864, and at the time of her loss was the property of Thomas Wall Stephens of [[London]] and him being the managing owner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mariners.records.nsw.gov.au/1881/12/019all.htm |title=Allahabad |publisher=Mariners.records.nsw.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2015-07-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185412/http://mariners.records.nsw.gov.au/1881/12/019all.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

''Allahabad'' last left [[Glasgow]] on 2 July 1886, with a crew of 20 and a cargo of 1,712 tons, of which 1,635 were coals, bound to [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]]. Having been signalled on 7 July off the Tuscar, she was on 4 September following, spoken, in about {{coord|29|S|28|W}} by ''South Australian''. From that time she has not been seen or heard of, and never arrived at her destination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plimsoll.org/resources/SCCLibraries/WreckReports/15310.asp |title=Wreck Report for 'Allahabad', 1887 - PortCities Southampton |publisher=Plimsoll.org |date=2007-10-26 |accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11588874 |title=4 Feb 1887 - ENGLISH SHIPPING INTELLIGENCE. [BY GABLE.&#93; |publisher=Trove.nla.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2015-07-23}}</ref>

