'''Anne Ector Pleasant''' (April 16, 1878 – September 13, 1934) was an American school teacher and founder of the private school Pleasant Hall in Shreveport which operated for more than fifty years. Between 1916 and 1920, she was the First Lady of Louisiana and though she supported women's suffrage, she was not in favor of passage of the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Nineteenth Amendment]], believing voting rights were a state rather than a federal issue.

==Early life==
Anne Ector was born on April 16, 1878 in [[Marshall, Texas]] to Sarah Parish "Sally" (née Chew) and General [[Mathew Ector|Matthew D. Ector]].{{sfn|''The Marshall Morning News''|1934|p=3}}{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1936|p=11}}{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1953|p=26}} Her father was a [[brigadier general]] in the [[Confederate States Army]], who was wounded during the [[Atlanta Campaign]] in 1864 and then returned to Texas where he served as a judge. At the time of his death in 1879, he was the presiding judge of the Court of Appeals.{{sfn|Lynch|1885|p=167}} Her mother was originally from Kentucky and after her husband's death raised Anne and her siblings, Helen, Walker and William.{{sfn|U. S. Census|1880|p=13}}{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1925|p=8}} Ector attended Belwood Seminary in [[Anchorage, Kentucky]] and went on to further her schooling at the [[Sam Houston Normal Institute]] in [[Huntsville, Texas]],{{sfn|''The Marshall Morning News''|1934|p=3}} graduating in 1899.{{sfn|''The Normal Bulletin''|1911|p=50}}

==Career==
After completing her education, Ector began teaching in Texas and taught for several years until her marriage on February 14, 1906 to [[Ruffin Pleasant]], who was the city attorney for Shreveport, Louisiana. After her marriage, Pleasant was active in the [[woman's club movement]], serving as president of the district [[General Federation of Women's Clubs|Federation of Women's Clubs]],{{sfn|''The Marshall Morning News''|1934|p=3}} while her husband served for six years as city attorney and then worked in private practice as a lawyer. He was appointed as assistant attorney general in 1911, causing the couple to move to [[New Orleans]] and then was made attorney general in 1912.{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1934|p=8}} After four years, he was elected as [[List of Governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]].{{sfn|Prime|2015|p=A-3}} During his governorship, Pleasant was active in the suffrage movement. While she was in favor of [[women's suffrage]], she was against the passage of the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], believing that states, rather than the federal government should determine who should be eligible to vote.{{sfn|Wheeler|1995|p=266}}

In 1920, when her term as First Lady ended, the couple returned to Shreveport. Within three years, Pleasant, who had been privately tutoring students in her home, opened Pleasant Hall, a private elementary school.{{sfn|Prime|2015|p=A-4}} The school focused on basic studies in reading, writing and arithmetic, but also offered instruction in French, English grammar and both music and art.{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1939|p=28}} Classes were held in the couple's home, which was located at 1703 Highland Avenue, on the corner with Wyandotte Street.{{sfn|Prime|2015|p=A-3}}{{sfn|Godfrey|1960|p=61}}

Pleasant was known as an opponent of Louisiana politician [[Huey Long]] and the two had a history of oral conflicts.{{sfn|'' The Weekly Town Talk''|1933|p=11}} In 1933, she made national headlines when she sued Long, alleging that while investigating documentation on nepotism and "questionable use and disposition" of the public's taxes in government institutions, she was removed from the courthouse, arrested and [[Defamation|slandered]] when Long called her a "drunken, cursing woman".{{sfn|''The Baltimore Sun''|1933|p=5}}{{sfn|''The Tampa Tribune|1933|p=4}} Initially, she asked for $250,000, but the amended her petition to double the amount, when she felt Long was trying to intimidate her.{{sfn|'' The Weekly Town Talk''|1933|p=11}}{{sfn|''The Tampa Tribune|1933|p=4}} Long tried to have the case dismissed on the grounds that under Louisiana law Pleasant could not sue in her own name, as under the state community property law, the suit would only be proper if filed in her husband's name. District Judge W. Carruth Jones rejected the argument based on similar cases that had been elevated to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]].{{sfn|'' The Weekly Town Talk''|1934|p=6}}

==Death and legacy==
Pleasant died on September 13, 1934, after being rushed to the hospital in Shreveport, having accidentally consumed poison when she drank an antiseptic, thinking it was her medicine.{{sfn||''The Marshall Morning News''|1934|p=1}}{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1934|p=1}} After her death, her husband took over the operation of Pleasant Hall and ran it until his death in 1937.{{sfn|''The Shreveport Times''|1939|p=28}} When he died, his sister, Mrs. Lucille Johnson took over the management of the school,{{sfn|Godfrey|1960|p=61}} which continued operating until the 1970s and maintained a reputation for its high educational standard in liberal arts. The home where the school was housed is noted by a tourist marker, as the last remaining home in Shreveport occupied by a state governor.{{sfn|Prime|2015|p=A-3}}

