{{refimprove|date=November 2014}} [[File:Émile Friant Guillaume Dubufe 1905.png|thumb|200px|Guillaume Dubufe; portrait by [[Émile Friant]] (1905)]] [[File:La Maison de la Vierge G.Dubufe.jpg|thumb|200px|The House of the Virgin (1890)]] '''Guillaume Édouard Marie Dubufe''' (16 May 1853, [[Paris]] &ndash; 25 May 1909, at sea, near [[Buenos Aires]]) was a French painter, decorator and illustrator.
== Biography == His father [[Édouard Louis Dubufe|Édouard]] was a painter and his mother {{ill|Juliette Dubufe|fr}} (the daughter of composer [[Pierre-Joseph-Guillaume Zimmermann]]) was a sculptor.<ref>[http://gw4.geneanet.org/index.php3?b=pdelaubier&lang=fr&m=N&v=Dubufe&cgl=o Genealogy of the artist] @ GeneaNet</ref> His grandfather, [[Claude Marie Paul Dubufe|Claude]], was also a painter and [[Charles Gounod]] was his uncle. Sadly, his mother died while giving birth to his sister Hortense when he was only two.
As might be expected, he received his first art lessons from his father, then pursued his studies at the [[École des Beaux-Arts]] under [[Alexis-Joseph Mazerolle]]. His first major commission involved decorating the ceiling of the foyer at the [[Comédie-Française]]<ref>[http://www.musee-orsay.fr/fr/collections/catalogue-des-oeuvres/resultat-collection.html?no_cache=1&zoom=1&tx_damzoom_pi1%5Bzoom%5D=0&tx_damzoom_pi1%5BxmlId%5D=009147&tx_damzoom_pi1%5Bback%5D=fr%2Fcollections%2Fcatalogue-des-oeuvres%2Fresultat-collection.html%3Fno_cache%3D1%26zsz%3D9 Sketch for the ceiling of the Comédie Française] @ the [[Musée d'Orsay]]</ref>
When not staying at their mansion in Paris, his family (he had five children) stayed at their villa in [[Anacapri]] on the [[Capri|Isle of Capri]], where he painted scenes of his home that would be exhibited in 1906 at the [[Georges Petit|Georges Petit Gallery]]. From 1888 to 1890, he produced a series of paintings featuring the [[Virgin Mary]]. During the 1890s, he decorated the ceilings of the Lobau Gallery at the [[Hôtel de Ville, Paris|Hôtel de Ville]], the banquet hall at the [[Élysée Palace]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=RANEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PT530 Encyclopedia Americana (1903)]</ref> and the library at the [[Sorbonne]]. In 1896, he designed and produced the décor for the "Salon National des Beaux-Arts". Four years later, he was one of several artists who provided decorations for [[Le Train Bleu (restaurant)|Le Train Bleu]], a famous restaurant near the [[Gare de Lyon]]. From 1906 to 1909, he and [[Édouard Rosset-Granger]] decorated the Town Hall of [[Saint-Mandé]]. He also illustrated several works by the French dramatist [[Émile Augier]].
He died at sea.{{clarify|date=November 2014}} His friend, the sculptor [[Albert Bartholomé]] provided the [[bas-relief]] for his memorial at [[Père Lachaise]] cemetery. In 1921, his mansion in Paris was acquired by Marie Henner, who turned it into a museum. It was donated to the French government in 1926, and is now known as the [[Musée national Jean-Jacques Henner]].
His daughter {{ill|Juliette Dubufe-Wehrlé|fr}}, also became a painter. [[File:Eros et Psyche - Guillaume Dubufe.jpg|thumb|Eros et Psyche]]
==Writings== * ''La Valeur de l'Art'', in the series, "Bibliothèque de philosophie scientifique", éditions E. Flammarion, 1908.
